  "prompt": "Would you support Gary Johnson's claim to be included in the presidential debates in the interest of fairness and an equitable playing field?",
  "response": "Including third-party candidates like Gary Johnson in presidential debates can indeed promote fairness and provide voters with a broader range of perspectives. The question is whether this inclusion aligns with the criteria set by debate organizers, typically the Commission on Presidential Debates (CPD), which requires candidates to demonstrate a minimum level of support (e.g., 15% in national polls) and have a viable path to the presidency.\n\nAs of the 2016 election, Johnson, representing the Libertarian Party, garnered significant attention but fell short of the CPD's polling threshold. While his inclusion could have enriched the discourse, the debate criteria aim to balance fairness with ensuring that participants have a realistic chance of winning, thus focusing the conversation on the most viable candidates.\n\nIn principle, broadening access to debates is commendable, but it must be balanced against the need to maintain a focused and substantive discussion among candidates with a credible chance of winning. If Johnson or other third-party candidates meet the established criteria, their inclusion would indeed contribute to a more equitable and diverse democratic process.",
